{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2007 |Team=Northwestern Wildcats |Image= Northwestern N logo.gif |Conference=Big Ten Conference |Division= |ShortConference=Big Ten |CoachRank= |APRank= |Record=6&ndash;6 |ConfRecord=3&ndash;5 |HeadCoach=[[Pat Fitzgerald]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[Ryan Field (stadium)|Ryan Field]] |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} {{2007 Big Ten football standings}} The '''2007 Northwestern Wildcats football team''' represented [[Northwestern University]] in the [[Big Ten Conference]] during the [[2007 NCAA Division I-BS football season|2007&ndash;2008]] [[college football]] season. [[Pat Fitzgerald]], in his second season at Northwestern, was the team's head coach. The Wildcats played their homes games at [[Ryan Field (stadium)|Ryan Field]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]].
Before the beginning of the 2007 season, Northwestern showed potential for improvement upon the previous year's record. [[ESPN.com]]'s [[Mark Schlabach]] stated that Northwestern has the seventh easiest schedule in college football, <ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=schlabach_mark&id=2924383 ESPN - Easy schedules should help these teams succeed - College Football<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and [[SI.com]]'s Steve Megargee claimed that [[2007 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]] was the only Big Ten school with an easier schedule.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/football/ncaa/06/18/schedules.bigten/2.html SI.com - NCAA Football - Big Ten schedule rankings (cont.) - Thursday June 21, 2007 1:32PM<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Running back]] [[Tyrell Sutton]] was one of 64 players in college football to be put on the [[Maxwell Award]] watch list for the nation's best college football player.<ref>[http://nusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/062607aaf.html Tyrell Sutton Named to Maxwell Award Watch List :: Sutton one of only 10 Big Ten players on list<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
The Wildcats began the season with their first shutout since 1997 in a 27-0 win against the {{cfb link|year=2007|team=Northeastern Huskies|title=Northeastern Huskies}}.<ref>[http://sports.yahoo.com/ncaaf/recap;_ylt=AuHMz9_O8k54KsVbDiB4LnAcvrYF?gid=200709010032 NCAA Football - Northeastern Huskies/Northwestern Wildcats Recap Saturday September 1, 2007 - Yahoo! Sports<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On October 7, [[quarterback]] C. J. Bacher broke [[Brett Basanez]]'s school record for single-game passing yards by throwing for 520 yards in a victory over [[2007 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]]. Bacher went on to be named the Walter Camp National Offensive Player of the Week and the Big Ten Conference Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>[http://nusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/100807aaa.html C.J. BachÃ©r Named Big Ten's Offensive Player of the Week :: Fans can also vote for C.J.; one of four nominees for the AT&T All-America Player of the Week award<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Another strong performance in a win against [[2007 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]] earned Bacher Big Ten Conference Offensive Player of the Week honors for the second week in a row.<ref>[http://nusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/101507aab.html Big Ten Honors Quarterback C.J. BachÃ©r Again With Offensive Player of the Week Award :: BachÃ©r also one of four nominees for the AT&T All-America Player of the Week award; fans can vote for C.J.!<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
